	doi = {10.3233/FAIA241359},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/85217168076?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {Online reviews significantly impact consumer behavior and shape perceptions of services in the digital marketplace. They serve as a vital source of information, influencing purchasing decisions and brand loyalty. As a result, businesses increasingly rely on managing their online reputation to attract and retain customers. With the growing reliance on online reviews in the hospitality industry, particularly for hotels, accurately analyzing customer feedback has become essential for improving service quality and enhancing guest satisfaction. However, processing and interpreting hotel reviews presents a significant challenge. This study addresses this issue by developing three widely used machine learning models: Naïve Bayes, Support Vector Machines (SVM), and Random Forest, to classify and evaluate hotel reviews gathered from the Google platform for hotels in Perak, Malaysia. Based on 2,993 samples, the analysis reveals that Naïve Bayes performs best overall with 76% accuracy and excels in detecting both positive and negative sentiments. SVM, with 70% accuracy, shows strong performance in detecting positive sentiments. On the other hand, Random Forest, with 74% accuracy, demonstrates high recall in detecting positive reviews but struggles with neutral sentiments. These results emphasize the necessity of choosing the right model according to specific evaluation metrics, especially in situations where customer feedback is diverse and complex.  © 2024 The Authors.},
