	abstract = {This paper explores sentiment analysis in Moroccan Arabic (Darija) using a large corpus of user-generated comments from the Hespress news platform. The dataset includes approximately 100,000 comments across five thematic categories (society, politics, economy, sports, and miscellaneous), annotated with sentiment labels (positive, neutral, negative). We evaluate both classical machine learning models (SVM, Naive Bayes, Logistic Regression, Random Forest) and a fine-tuned transformer model (MARBERT) pretrained on dialectal Arabic data. Text preprocessing includes cleaning, normalization, and transliteration from Latin (Frarabic) to Arabic script. Results show that MARBERT significantly outperforms classical baselines, achieving a macro-F1 score of 0.78 and an accuracy of 0,84. A complementary qualitative analysis highlights the influence of script usage, regional vocabulary, and tone on sentiment expression. The study underlines the importance of dialect-aware NLP methods and opens perspectives for integrating sociolinguistic cues into future sentiment classification tasks.  © 2025 The Authors. Published by Elsevier B.V.},
